  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "Sound is a form of energy produced by vibrating objects. Sound requires a medium (solid, liquid, or gas) to travel and cannot travel through vacuum. Sound travels fastest in solids, slower in liquids, and slowest in gases. The speed of sound in air is approximately 343 m/s. Sound has three characteristics: loudness (related to amplitude), pitch (related to frequency), and quality/timbre (distinguishes different sources). Frequency is measured in Hertz (Hz). Sound waves are longitudinal waves with compressions (high pressure) and rarefactions (low pressure). The relationship between speed, frequency, and wavelength is v = fλ.",
    "rules": [
      "Sound is produced by vibrating objects.",
      "Sound requires a medium to travel.",
      "Sound cannot travel through vacuum.",
      "Speed of sound: solid > liquid > gas",
      "Loudness depends on amplitude.",
      "Pitch depends on frequency.",
      "Quality (timbre) distinguishes different sound sources.",
      "Frequency is measured in Hertz (Hz).",
      "v = fλ (velocity = frequency × wavelength)"
    ]
  },
